<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
  <meta charset="UTF-8">
  <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0">
  <title>Skyway Ground Crew · Admin Console</title>
  <link rel="stylesheet" href="/css/style.css">
</head>
<body>
  <div class="challenge-page">
    <a href="/challenge/8" class="back-link">← Back to Day 8</a>
    <div class="brand brand-sm">
      <span class="brand-mark">⛨</span>
      <span>CySER Workshop · Skyway engagement</span>
    </div>

    <div class="challenge-header">
      <h1>👑 Admin Console</h1>
      <p class="desc">Authentication accepted. Welcome, <code><%= payload.sub %></code>.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="challenge-content">
      <div class="story-box">
        The verifier trusted your forged token because its header advertises <code>alg: "none"</code>. In production
        this misconfig has led to real-world account takeovers. The spec lets the algorithm be "none", but no
        sane verifier should accept it.
      </div>

      <h2>Admin secret</h2>
      <pre class="code-block" style="font-size:1.15em; color:#981E32;"><%= flag %></pre>

      <p style="margin-top:20px;">Copy the flag above and submit it on <a href="/challenge/8">Day 8</a>.</p>
    </div>
  </div>
</body>
</html>
